“Non-material cultural heritage” is another name for intangible cultural heritage.  
It is the part of a people’s heritage that is not a monument or an artefact but consists of living practices, expressions and knowledge that communities recognise as their own and transmit from generation to generation.  

It therefore includes, for example:  
• oral traditions and languages;  
• performing arts such as music, dance, theatre, storytelling;  
• social customs, rituals, festivals and religious practices;  
• traditional craftsmanship skills and the know-how used to make objects;  
• knowledge and practices concerning nature, the universe, food, medicine, etc.  

Unlike tangible heritage (buildings, archaeological sites, works of art), non-material or intangible heritage exists primarily in people’s memory, behaviour and skill, and it is kept alive by being practised, taught and adapted over time.
